Duolingo changed the way I learn languages. The app's gamified approach makes language learning not just educational but also incredibly fun. The bite-sized lessons are perfect for someone like me with a busy schedule, allowing me to squeeze in learning during short breaks. Because of the so-called "streaks" I practice my skills everyday. The listening, speaking, and writing exercises are interactive and effective in improving all aspects of language proficiency. Highly recommend!

Duolingo has been working well for me. I'm studying Korean, and I'm definitely learning to understand everything. However, there are a few reasons I can only give it three stars. Some of the pronunciations are very confusing, and you have to learn the entire alphabet before you can even consider beginning the actual course. Duolingo gives no explanation for how combining letters works, and you have to find that out another way. Finally, features are hard to access, and the layout is awkward.

This is a great novice course for any language. I'm taking the Spanish. I will say some things aren't perfect but you can also use Google translate to get some terms corrected. I'm on unit 12 and they haven't taught the -iendo yet. They would rather say I learn *yo aprendo* versus I am learning *yo esoy apriendo* but the good thing about this is they'll have a side bar section where people that have also taken these courses will give extra lessons or corrections

Lots of people will say Duolingo is an ineffective way to learn a language, but using it often, skipping sections when they repeat what you know and reviewing old sections, along with using reliable translators like word reference and attempting to translate songs etc. outside the app with minimal help, using Duolingo as your base guide, has been very effective for me. The app won't teach you everything you want to know immediately, but that should be expected. Plus it's of course free!
